    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-07T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-07T07:00:00-05:00" n="166"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860F.51/11–746: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gallman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-07T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 7, 1946—noon.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 7—8:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9336. Mytel 9261, November 5 and 89 to Praha.<note n="86" xml:id="d166fn86">Not
                        printed; it reported that Clementis, who was stopping 3 days in London en
                        route to the United Nations meeting in New York, had paid a widely
                        publicized call on Prime Minister Attlee (860F.51/11–546).</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> official charged Czech Affairs states
                    that when Attlee received Clementis latter immediately introduced question
                    British credits to Czecho and afterwards sought to explain Czech position on US
                    loan declaring “Czech Govt was convinced US action was solely on grounds of
                    Czech attitude at Paris Conference” to which Attlee responded that he was <pb
                        facs="0249" n="235" xml:id="pg_235"/> aware that “Secretary Byrnes and
                    others were displeased with the action of Czechs at Paris” and concluded
                    interview by counselling Clementis “upon his arrival in US to take steps at once
                    to come to an understanding with US authorities.”</p>
                <p>Official added interview was very satisfactory from <gloss target="#t_FonOff1"
                        >FonOff</gloss> viewpoint, that Clementis in attitude and approach is
                    typical of Soviet stooges in satellite Govts, and that he is being sent to UN
                    meeting to “keep Masaryk in line.”</p>
                <p>Repeated Praha 91.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gallman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
